SIMPLE: liking
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Liking
<hw>Lik"ing</hw> <pr>(l⟦imac⟧k"⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>, <pos>p. a.</pos>
<def>Looking; appearing; <as>as, better or worse <ex>liking</ex></as>.
See <er>Like</er>, to look.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Why should he see your faces worse <qex>liking</qex> than the
children which are of your sort?</q> <rj><qau>Dan. i. 10.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Liking</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Liking
<hw>Lik"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The state of being
pleasing; a suiting. See <cref>On liking</cref>, below.</def>
<mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The state of being pleased with, or attracted
toward, some thing or person; hence, inclination; desire; pleasure;
preference; -- often with <ptcl>for</ptcl>, formerly with
<ptcl>to</ptcl>; <as>as, it is an amusement I have no <ex>liking</ex>
for</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>If the human intellect hath once taken a <qex>liking</qex> to any
doctrine, . . . it draws everything else into harmony with that
doctrine, and to its support.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Appearance; look; figure; state of body as to health
or condition.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I shall think the worse of fat men, as long as I have an eye to
make difference of men's <qex>liking</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their young ones are in good <qex>liking</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Job.
xxxix. 4.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>On liking</b></col>, <cd>on condition of being pleasing
to or suiting; also, on condition of being pleased with; as, to hold a
place of service <xex>on liking</xex>; to engage a servant <xex>on
liking</xex>.</cd> <mark>[Obs. or Prov. Eng.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Would he be the degenerate scion of that royal line . . . to be a
king <xex>on liking</xex> and on sufferance?</q>
<rj><qau>Hazlitt.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lilac</ent>⟦br⟧
